   (Message) ROOT CAUSE: `/mnt/c/Users/Owner/OneDrive/Documents/Classes/COS/COS4
   84/chatdbgpro/bench/cases/paper/test-use-after-free/program.cpp:10-11`
   corrupts the only owning pointer before deletion: `new int(100)` returns the
   allocation base, observed as `0x502000000010`, but `n--` changes `n` to
   `0x50200000000c`, four bytes before the allocated `int`. The stopped program
   is in `operator delete`/ASan deallocation at line 11 with `n ==
   0x50200000000c`, so `delete n;` is not being passed the exact pointer
   returned by `new`; that is undefined behavior and ASan crashes/reports it
   before the later intended dangling dereference at `doSomething(n)`. If
   execution continued past that, `doSomething(n)` and `std::cout << *n` would
   also be invalid because `n` would either point before the allocation or to
   freed storage.
   
   LOCAL FIX: Preserve the allocation pointer and do not use it after deletion;
   perform the work while the object is still alive, then delete exactly the
   pointer returned by `new`. For example:```diff
    int main()
    {
      int * n = new int(100);
   -  n--;
   -  delete n;
      char * ch = new char[16];
      delete [] ch;
      doSomething(n);
      std::cout << "n = " << *n << std::endl;
   +  delete n;
      return 0;
    }
   ``` This removes the invalid pointer decrement, avoids deleting a non-base
   address, and ensures `doSomething(n)` and `*n` occur before `delete n`.
   
   GLOBAL FIX: Replace raw owning pointers with RAII ownership types so pointer
   arithmetic and manual lifetime mistakes are not possible at the call site,
   e.g. use `auto n = std::make_unique<int>(100); doSomething(n.get());
   std::cout << "n = " << *n << std::endl;` and `std::array<char, 16>` or
   `std::vector<char>` for the character buffer. More broadly, separate
   ownership from access by passing `int&` or a non-owning bounded/view type to
   `doSomething` instead of a raw mutable pointer, and maintain the invariant
   that only owning RAII objects release memory while borrowed references/views
   cannot delete or outlive the owner.
